# Unit Testing

## Framework
- JUnit 5 (or JUnit 6 with Spring Framework 7)
- AssertJ for fluent assertions: `assertThat(result).isEqualTo(expected)`
- Mockito with `MockitoExtension` for dependency mocking

## Test Structure
- Given-When-Then pattern (Arrange-Act-Assert)
- One assertion concept per test method
- Descriptive names: `shouldCalculateTotalWithDiscount`, `shouldThrowWhenInputIsNull`
- `@DisplayName` for human-readable names in reports

## Annotations
- `@Test`, `@BeforeEach`, `@AfterEach` for lifecycle
- `@Nested` for grouping related tests
- `@ParameterizedTest` with `@ValueSource`, `@CsvSource`, `@MethodSource`
- `@Disabled("reason")` with explanation -- never disable without reason

## Mocking
- `@Mock` for dependencies, `@InjectMocks` for the class under test
- Stub with `when().thenReturn()`, verify with `verify()`
- Never mock the class under test
- Prefer fakes or stubs over mocks when behavior is simple

## Assertions
- AssertJ over JUnit assertions for readability
- `assertThatThrownBy(() -> ...)` for exception testing
- `assertThat(list).hasSize(3).contains(item)` for collection assertions

## Anti-Patterns
- Testing implementation details instead of behavior
- Using reflection to access private members
- Shared mutable state between tests
- Hard-coded test data without explanation

